  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2592063719?book_show_action=true">May 18, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Michael" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Michael" href="/user/show/3506592-michael">Michael</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Mass Market Paperback " href="/book/show/2529642.A_Stillness_at_Appomattox">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3506592-michael?shelf=history">history</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3506592-michael?shelf=nonfiction">nonfiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2592063719" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5613623389524509244">A few years ago, I watched a brief documentary about the life and work of the author David McCoullouh (I think it was attached to the end of the HBO miniseries<i> John Adams</i>). In the interview, he mentioned that one of his favorite history books--and one that set him on this course toward becoming a professional writer--was a book called <i>A Stillness at Appomattox</i>. I kept my eyes open for a copy and a few months ago, found one. <br/><br/>The paperback I read was printed in 1963. The cover art, the red colored</span>
  <span id="freeText5613623389524509244" style="display:none">A few years ago, I watched a brief documentary about the life and work of the author David McCoullouh (I think it was attached to the end of the HBO miniseries<i> John Adams</i>). In the interview, he mentioned that one of his favorite history books--and one that set him on this course toward becoming a professional writer--was a book called <i>A Stillness at Appomattox</i>. I kept my eyes open for a copy and a few months ago, found one. <br /><br />The paperback I read was printed in 1963. The cover art, the red colored page edges, and the smell of the book (yes, I like the smell of old books) took me back in time to my grandparents' house when I was a boy. They had dozens of books of this vintage (although, at the time, the books were probably 15 years old, not fifty 56!) The paperback is in mint condition, and it was a joy to read, physically. They just don't make paperbacks this way anymore. <br /><br />The author, who won the Pulitzer Prize for this work in the early 1950s, writes beautifully, even poetically. His language is almost dreamy in places, and while there was a bit too much detail about which brigade and which core was led by what officer performing what maneuver (hey, it's military history), I was utterly captivated by his telling of this story. At one point, when Catton was describing the battle between Union General Phillip Sheridan and Confederate General Jubal Early in the Shennedoah Valley, I couldn't put the book down. It's not like I didn't know who won! It is simply gripping writing. Excellent, excellent writing. <br /><br />I've done some reading about the Civil War before, most memorably <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/35100.Battle_Cry_of_Freedom" title="Battle Cry of Freedom by James M. McPherson" rel="nofollow noopener">Battle Cry of Freedom</a> and James Stokebury's <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/35799.A_Short_History_of_the_Civil_War" title="A Short History of the Civil War by James L. Stokesbury" rel="nofollow noopener">A Short History of the Civil War</a>, but it's been a while. This particular book focused entirely on the final year of the war, and the brutal fighting at the Wilderness, Cold Harbor, the Battle of the Crater, and the final, World War I-like trench warfare near the Confederate capital of Richmond. I would have liked to have read more about Robert E. Lee's experiences during this time; the book was told entirely from the Union's point of view...but it's not like there is a lack of books out there about the Civil War! There is more I'd like to know about.<br /><br />In the end, the North won and the South lost. I do not like to judge people in the past for the decisions they made, because--just as we do today--they did the best they could in the circumstances in which they found themselves. It occurs to me though that Lincoln may have been a bit too generous with the terms of the Confederate surrender. Maybe he should have hung, or at least imprisoned, Jefferson Davis and Robert E. Lee. Maybe the federal government should have disallowed the building of Confederate monuments, and the fetishization of Confederate flags that started forty or fifty years after the war's end. Maybe people in the south should be taught that the war was not, in fact, about 'stats rats' (that is, 'state's rights' in actual English), and that it was, 100%, fully, inarguably, about slavery and the keeping of slaves. Would our history be different had those choices been made? I don't know.<br /><br />Anyhow, very good history book. Well worth reading. One Confederate solider, near the end of the hostilities, said 'this is a rich man's war but a poor man's fight.' Ain't the truth? </span>
  <a data-text-id="5613623389524509244" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

