  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3390545780" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3390545780" />
    <a title="Patrick McNamara" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/116843771-patrick-mcnamara"><img alt="Patrick McNamara" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1592060353p2/116843771.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3390545780?book_show_action=true">Jun 13, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Patrick McNamara" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Patrick McNamara" href="/user/show/116843771-patrick-mcnamara">Patrick McNamara</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3390545780" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9226326527056099538">In the year 1954, Bruce Catton’s A Stillness at Appomattox, a book about the Civil War’s last year, won both the National Book Award and the Pulitzer. My mother, who read it that year, considered it her favorite history book. Early on she imparted to me a love of history that’s grown through the years. Among my own first books was Catton’s history of the Civil War, published for the centennial.<br/><br/>I cherish it dearly. To this day the images therein remain with me: a Yankee officer rallying his men a</span>
  <span id="freeText9226326527056099538" style="display:none">In the year 1954, Bruce Catton’s A Stillness at Appomattox, a book about the Civil War’s last year, won both the National Book Award and the Pulitzer. My mother, who read it that year, considered it her favorite history book. Early on she imparted to me a love of history that’s grown through the years. Among my own first books was Catton’s history of the Civil War, published for the centennial.<br /><br />I cherish it dearly. To this day the images therein remain with me: a Yankee officer rallying his men at Perryville, Jeb Stuart’s bright eyes and bushy beard, a determined Grant leaning against a tree, Confederate soldiers weeping as they roll up their battle flags. I still remember the first line: “The American people in 1860 believed they were the luckiest people in the world. And in a way they were right.” <br /><br />At Fordham, I took classes on the Civil War era with a professor who opened my eyes to the era’s larger socio-political context, as opposed to just steel blades and brass buttons. Later Ken Burns’s groundbreaking documentary The Civil War gripped me with its haunting images and music. <br /><br />Since then, I’ve read some great and some not so great books. Thanks to assiduous scholarly research, we know more about the war than ever before. But today while many historians emphasize research over narrative, we also need books that are readable for the general public. <br /><br />A professional journalist, Catton wrote as few historians have. But it’s not just his style, but because he understood the Union soldier. For example, listen to the introduction to his book Mr. Lincoln’s Army: <br /><br />The books which make up this trilogy began, very simply as an attempt to understand the men who fought in the Army of the Potomac. As a small boy I had known a number of these men in their old age; they were grave, dignified, and thoughtful, with long white beards and a general air of being pillars of the community. They lived in rural Michigan in the pre-automobile age, and for the most part they had never been fifty miles away from the farm or the dusty village streets; yet once, ages ago, they had been everywhere and seen everything… <br /><br />After receiving my doctorate, I felt incapable of reading history for pleasure, at least until I encountered read Catton’s trilogy: Mr. Lincoln’s Army, Glory Road, and A Stillness. A friend argued that Catton was the best Civil War historian ever. His enthusiasm encouraged me to try Catton. I couldn’t put him down. <br /><br />No historian captured those who fought for the Union across five Aprils. Now, like many historians, I too consider him among the best. I back constantly, because I feel he nailed it, just as Stephen Ambrose did for the American G.I. in World War II. Catton captured a world long gone, as only the best historians can do. That’s why he still matters. It’s also why I continue to read history, to reconnect with those who came before us. <br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="9226326527056099538" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


